results.abstract: Aaron Cohen, engineer who worked on Apollo moon program, dies at age 79; photo (S)

headline.main: Aaron Cohen, 79, Official And Engineer With NASA

results.snippet: Mr. Cohen worked on the Apollo moon program, the space shuttles and the space station during a 30-year career with the agency.
results.lead_paragraph: Aaron Cohen, an engineer who worked on the spacecraft used in the Apollo moon program and who later, as director of the Johnson Space Center, helped NASA recover after the Challenger explosion, died Feb. 25 at his home in College Station, Tex. He was 79. The cause was prostate cancer, which he had been fighting for years, said one of his sons, Daniel.

results.abstract: Dina Ingersole is restoring F9F Cougar, 1950s era Navy aircraft that now resides on deck of Intrepid Sea, Air and Space Museum; she volunteers her time and expertise for this self-described labor of love; photo (M)

headline.main: Restoring a Museum Piece, A Jungle Gym That Once Flew

results.snippet: At the Intrepid Sea, Air and Space Museum in New York, a Grumman fighter jet is painstakingly restored.
results.lead_paragraph: THE Grumman F9F Cougar had seen better days, some of them flying in Navy fighter squadrons in the 1950s. But then it was retired and ended up spending years in a park in New Jersey as perhaps the world's coolest jungle gym. Now it's a mess -- the once-smooth metal skin rough and spotted, holes here and there. The fuselage is in two pieces. And the wings have been taken off, which, for a high-performance jet aircraft, is a real insult.

results.snippet: Beijing should stop issuing cryptic comments about Gao Zhisheng's fate and give concrete information about his health and whereabouts.

byline.original: By JEROME A. COHEN and BETH SCHWANKE

results.lead_paragraph: Peter Gao is six and wants to be an astronaut. If you ask him why, he'll explain that he wanted to be a lawyer, but the Chinese government ''really hates lawyers.'' He's pretty sure that it likes astronauts. The Chinese government ''disappeared'' Peter's father, Gao Zhisheng, on Feb. 4, 2009. According to various Chinese officials over the past year, Mr. Gao is, ''in Beijing,'' ''gone missing,'' ''where he should be,'' ''working in Urumqi,'' the capital of China's northwestern Xinjiang Province, and now ''sentenced for subversion.''

results.abstract: Report by American Assn of University Women on underrepresentation of women in science and math finds that although women have made gains, stereotypes and cultural biases still impede their success; treads lightly on hot-button question of whether innate differences between sexes account for paucity of women at highest levels of science and math; photo; graph; charts (M)

headline.main: Bias Called Persistent Hurdle for Women in Sciences

results.snippet: A report sought recommendations for drawing more women into science, technology, engineering and mathematics.
results.lead_paragraph: A report on the underrepresentation of women in science and math by the American Association of University Women, to be released Monday, found that although women have made gains, stereotypes and cultural biases still impede their success. The report, ''Why So Few?,'' supported by the National Science Foundation, examined decades of research to cull recommendations for drawing more women into science, technology, engineering and mathematics, the so-called STEM fields.

(Showtime) NURSE JACKIE Season 2 opens with Jackie Peyton (Edie Falco) seeking redemption from her indiscretions by renewing her commitment to Kevin (Dominic Fumusa, above with Ms. Falco) and their daughters (Ruby Jerins and Mackenzie Aladjem) and spending a lot of time in the All Saints chapel. But Eddie (Paul Schulze) -- the hospital's former pharmacist and Jackie's former drug dispenser and lover -- doesn't make it any easier when he shows up in the emergency room after overdosing. In the season premiere of ''United States of Tara,'' at 10:30, Tara Gregson (Toni Collette) has enjoyed life without dissociation for several months, so she decides to make some friends with the help of her husband, Max (John Corbett). Then a neighbor commits suicide and leaves the Gregsons with responsibility for the house and estate. 8 P.M. (BBC America) TOP GEAR Jeremy Clarkson, Richard Hammond and James May do their part to save the planet by building an electric car with batteries from a milk float, a delivery vehicle common in Britain. They then tour Oxford before submitting their creation to the new-car testing process. Later the men head to the track for a battle of the continents, with North America represented by the Chevrolet Corvette ZR1 and Europe by the Audi R8 V10. Michael Sheen of ''Frost/Nixon'' is the star in a reasonably priced car.

headline.main: In a 5-Minute Grace Period, A Number of Possibilities

results.snippet: So Monday was the day the five-minute grace period started. That gave time-pressed drivers in New York five extra minutes to move their cars after alternate-side regulations take effect.     Or five extra minutes to put more money in a parking meter...
results.lead_paragraph: So Monday was the day the five-minute grace period started. That gave time-pressed drivers in New York five extra minutes to move their cars after alternate-side regulations take effect. Or five extra minutes to put more money in a parking meter or do the Muni Meter dance. You know the steps: Take a new ticket from the Muni Meter, unlock the car, grab the old ticket, place the new ticket on the dashboard, close the car door and look to see that the ticket did not blow away as the door closed.

results.abstract: Robert M White, pilot who broke limits in flight, dies at age 85; photo (M)

headline.main: Robert M. White, 85; Broke Limits in Flight

results.snippet: Mr. White played an important role in the development of manned spaceflight as the first pilot to fly a winged craft into outer space.
results.lead_paragraph: Robert M. White, who played an important role in the development of manned spaceflight as the first pilot to fly a winged craft into outer space, died Wednesday in Orlando, Fla. He was 85. His death was announced by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.

results.snippet: Tell us what qualities you think it takes to win "Dancing with the Stars" and who is your top pick for this season?
results.lead_paragraph: There's only been one episode of performances so far this season, but "Dancing With the Stars" has already broken a series record, averaging 23.9 million viewers on Monday night. As in years past, the show, now in its 10th edition, pairs 11 quasi-celebrities with 11 professional dancers, and promises to deliver a hard-to-resist mix of spray tans, awkward moves, cheesy comments and sequins.

results.abstract: New York City Housing Authority is at loss to explain decision to order jail jungle gym for playground at Tompkins Houses in Brooklyn; authority removed 'jail' sign and bars after complaints from residents; Landscape Structures, Minnesota company that authority says produced equipment, declined to comment on whether similar versions of playset had been sold elsewhere; photo (M)

headline.main: Playground's Jail Theme Is Gone, but Perplexity Lingers

results.snippet: A “jail” sign on a jungle gym at a public housing complex in Brooklyn has been painted over.

byline.original: By ELISSA GOOTMAN and CARA BUCKLEY; Ann Farmer contributed reporting

results.lead_paragraph: Building a playground is not as simple as installing a set of vertigo-inspiring monkey bars: These days, the world of playground design is rife with debate over how high the slides should be, whether the equipment should be brightly colored (kids say yes) or blend in with the environment, and whether themes like castles and rocket ships stimulate or stifle the imagination. But those who think about playgrounds for a living, as scholars, manufacturers and children's advocates, were united in their bafflement on Thursday over a playground at a Brooklyn housing project featuring a pretend jail with bars and a cell door.
